### Swift Classes

Classes are reference types that support inheritance, deinitializers, and multiple references to the same instance. They are fundamental building blocks of object-oriented programming in Swift.

**Class Definition:**

```swift
class ClassName {
    // Properties
    var property: Type = defaultValue

    // Initializer
    init(parameter: Type) {
        self.property = parameter
    }

    // Methods
    func methodName() {
        // Code
    }
}

class Person {
    var name: String
    var age: Int

    init(name: String, age: Int) {
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
    }

    func introduce() -> String {
        return "Hi, I'm \(name) and I'm \(age) years old"
    }
}

let alice = Person(name: "Alice", age: 30)
print(alice.introduce())
```

**Key Characteristics of Classes:**

| Feature | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| Reference type | Assigned by reference, not by value |
| Inheritance | Can inherit from another class |
| Deinitializer | `deinit` called when instance is destroyed |
| Multiple references | Multiple variables can point to same instance |
| Mutability | Can modify properties even with `let` reference |

```swift
// Reference type behavior
let person1 = Person(name: "Bob", age: 25)
let person2 = person1  // Both point to same instance
person2.name = "Robert"
print(person1.name)  // "Robert" - changed!
```

> **Key Point:** Classes are reference types meaning when you assign a class instance to a new variable, both variables reference the same object in memory.

Classes must define initializers for all stored properties that don't have default values.

codeExample:
import Foundation

class BankAccount {
    let accountNumber: String
    var balance: Double
    let owner: String

    init(owner: String, initialBalance: Double) {
        self.owner = owner
        self.balance = initialBalance
        self.accountNumber = "ACC-\(Int.random(in: 1000...9999))"
    }

    func deposit(amount: Double) {
        balance += amount
        print("\(owner) deposited $\(amount). New balance: $\(balance)")
    }

    func withdraw(amount: Double) -> Bool {
        if amount <= balance {
            balance -= amount
            print("\(owner) withdrew $\(amount). New balance: $\(balance)")
            return true
        }
        print("Insufficient funds")
        return false
    }
}

let account = BankAccount(owner: "Alice", initialBalance: 1000)
account.deposit(amount: 500)
account.withdraw(amount: 200)
print("Account \(account.accountNumber): $\(account.balance)")
